==English ==




== Etymology ==


There are many theories as to where this idiom comes from, but a plausible one is as follows:

    * Victorian morality shunned mention of a woman's leg, or portion thereof; the phrase '''second joint''' was coined to avoid use of the work '''thigh''' ;

[edit]

==Verb phrase ==


second joint

   1. (idiomatic, euphemism) The upper leg of a cooked fowl, e.g. a chicken or turkey thigh

          The drumstick of a turkey is connected to the second joint.

 [edit]

==Synonyms==

   1.  Thigh